{
  "local_port": 39432,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the standard puzzles asked in programming interviews?",
  "response": "Programming interviews often include a variety of puzzles and problems designed to test a candidate's problem-solving skills, coding ability, and understanding of algorithms and data structures. Below is a list of standard types of puzzles and problems commonly asked in programming interviews:\n\n---\n\n### **1. String Manipulation**\n   - Reverse a string.\n   - Check if a string is a palindrome.\n   - Find the first non-repeating character in a string.\n   - Find the longest substring without repeating characters.\n   - Implement string matching algorithms (e.g., KMP, Rabin-Karp).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Array and Matrix Problems**\n   - Find the maximum subarray sum (Kadane\u2019s Algorithm).\n   - Find duplicates in an array.\n   - Rotate an array.\n   - Search in a sorted and rotated array.\n   - Spiral traversal of a matrix.\n   - Set matrix zeros.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Linked List**\n   - Reverse a linked list.\n   - Detect a cycle in a linked list.\n   - Find the intersection point of two linked lists.\n   - Merge two sorted linked lists.\n   - Remove duplicates from a sorted/unsorted linked list.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Binary Trees and Binary Search Trees (BST)**\n   - Traversal problems (Inorder, Preorder, Postorder, Level Order).\n   - Check if a binary tree is balanced.\n   - Find the lowest common ancestor (LCA) in a BST or binary tree.\n   - Validate a BST.\n   - Convert a sorted array to a balanced BST.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Dynamic Programming**\n   - 0/1 Knapsack problem.\n   - Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS).\n   - Longest Common Subsequence (LCS).\n   - Coin change problem.\n   - Fibonacci sequence (memoization and tabulation).\n\n---\n\n### **6. Graph Algorithms**\n   - Breadth-First Search (BFS) and Depth-First Search (DFS).\n   - Detect a cycle in a graph.\n   - Topological sorting.\n   - Shortest path algorithms (Dijkstra\u2019s, Bellman-Ford, Floyd-Warshall).\n   - Minimum Spanning Tree (Kruskal\u2019s, Prim\u2019s).\n\n---\n\n### **7. Searching and Sorting**\n   - Binary search and its variations.\n   - Implement sorting algorithms (QuickSort, MergeSort, HeapSort).\n   - Find the kth smallest/largest element in an array.\n   - Merge two sorted arrays.\n   - Sort an array of 0s, 1s, and 2s (Dutch National Flag problem).\n\n---\n\n### **8. Bit Manipulation**\n   - Count the number of set bits (Hamming Weight).\n   - Find the single number in an array where all other numbers appear twice.\n   - Check if a number is a power of two.\n   - Swap two numbers without using a temporary variable.\n   - Find the missing number in a range.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Recursion and Backtracking**\n   - Generate all permutations of a string.\n   - Solve the N-Queens problem.\n   - Subset sum problem.\n   - Generate all valid parentheses combinations.\n   - Rat in a Maze problem.\n\n---\n\n### **10. System Design (for experienced candidates)**\n   - Design a URL shortening service (e.g., TinyURL).\n   - Design a social media news feed.\n   - Design a parking lot system.\n   - Design a search engine.\n   - Design a distributed cache system.\n\n---\n\n### **11. Time and Space Complexity Analysis**\n   - Analyze and optimize the time and space complexity of given code or algorithms.\n   - Discuss trade-offs between different approaches.\n\n---\n\n### **12. Miscellaneous Problems**\n   - Two Sum problem.\n   - Trapping Rain Water problem.\n   - Container With Most Water problem.\n   - Sliding Window problems (e.g., maximum sum of subarrays of size k).\n   - Implement a stack using queues and vice versa.\n\n---\n\n### Tips for Solving Puzzles:\n1. **Understand the Problem:** Clarify constraints and edge cases.\n2. **Break It Down:** Start with a brute-force approach, then optimize.\n3. **Use Appropriate Data Structures:** Choose the right tool for the problem (e.g., hash maps, heaps, stacks).\n4. **Test Your Code:** Check for edge cases and correctness.\n5. **Practice Regularly:** Use platforms like LeetCode, HackerRank, and Codeforces to build familiarity.\n\nBy practicing these types of problems and understanding the underlying concepts, you can prepare effectively for programming interviews.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
